Here is an example of VHDL code for a 4:1 multiplexer (MUX) using the selected signal assignment statement:
```
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity mux4to1 is
    Port ( a, b, c, d : in  STD_LOGIC;
           sel : in  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR(1 downto 0);
           y : out  STD_LOGIC);
end mux4to1;

architecture Behavioral of mux4to1 is
begin
    y <= a when sel = "00" else
         b when sel = "01" else
         c when sel = "10" else
         d;
end Behavioral;
```
In this example, the entity "mux4to1" has four input signals (a, b, c, d) and one output signal (y) and one input signal sel (2 bit) to select one of the four inputs to be passed to the output.

In the architecture "Behavioral", the output signal "y" is assigned a value based on the value of the input signal "sel" using the selected signal assignment statement. The "when" clause specifies that the output "y" should be assigned the value of input "a" when "sel" is equal to "00", the value of input "b" when "sel" is equal to "01", the value of input "c" when "sel" is equal to "10", and the value of input "d" when "sel" is equal to "11".

This code can be simulated and implemented on an FPGA or ASIC to create a 4:1 multiplexer.

