Yes, you **can** call C# code from a **Blazor Server component** that is **rendered within a Razor page**, and you can use that to **open a DxPopup** from a **TinyMCE toolbar button**.

Here’s how you can do it step-by-step:

---

### ✅ **1. Add the DxPopup in a Blazor Server Component**

Create a Blazor Server component (e.g., `PopupComponent.razor`) that contains the `DxPopup` and has a `@ref` to it.

```razor
@page "/popup-component"

@using DevExtreme.Blazor.Components

<DxPopup @ref="popup" ContentRenderMode="ContentRenderMode.Compact" Width="400" Height="200" ShowCloseButton="true">
    <Content>
        <p>This is the content of the popup.</p>
    </Content>
</DxPopup>

@code {
    private DxPopup popup;

    public void ShowPopup()
    {
        popup.Show();
    }
}
```

---

### ✅ **2. Use the Component in a Razor Page**

In your Razor page (e.g., `Index.cshtml`), include the component and use it as a child of the `body` or another container.

```html
@page "/"

@using YourBlazorApp.Pages
@using YourBlazorApp.Components

<PopupComponent />

<!-- Your TinyMCE editor -->
<textarea id="my-editor"></textarea>

@section Scripts {
    <script src="https://cdn.tiny.cloud/1/no-api-key/tinymce/6/tinymce.min.js" referrerpolicy="origin"></script>
    <script>
        tinymce.init({
            selector: '#my-editor',
            toolbar: 'mybutton',
            setup: function (editor) {
                editor.ui.registry.addButton('mybutton', {
                    text: 'Show Popup',
                    icon: 'fas fa-star',
                    onAction: function () {
                        // Call the C# method using DotNet.invokeMethodAsync
                        DotNet.invokeMethodAsync('YourBlazorApp', 'ShowPopup', 'PopupComponent')
                            .catch(function (err) {
                                console.error(err);
                            });
                    }
                });
            }
        });
    </script>
}
```

> ⚠️ **Note:** In the `DotNet.invokeMethodAsync` call, the first argument is the **assembly name** (e.g., `YourBlazorApp`), the second is the **method name**, and the third is the **component name** (e.g., `PopupComponent`) — this is how Blazor identifies which component to call the method on.

---

### ✅ **3. Expose the C# Method in the Component**

In your `PopupComponent.razor.cs` file, make sure the `ShowPopup` method is public:

```csharp
public partial class PopupComponent
{
    public void ShowPopup()
    {
        popup.Show();
    }
}
```

---

### ✅ **4. Ensure the Component Is Registered (if needed)**

If the component is not in the default `Pages` folder or is in a subfolder, make sure it's properly registered in your `Program.cs` (for Blazor Server):

```csharp
builder.Services.AddRazorPages();
builder.Services.AddServerSideBlazor();
```

And ensure that the component is in the correct namespace.

---

### ✅ **5. Optional: Add Font Awesome**

Make sure you're using Font Awesome in your Blazor app. Add this to your `_Host.cshtml` or `_Layout.cshtml`:

```html
